HB1689
1 recruiters of the state and the United States to enable those official
2 recruiting representatives to inform students of educational and career
3 opportunities available in the military.
4 (b) If a public high school does not grant access within the public
5 high school to prospective employers, institutions of higher education,
6 career entities, educational entities, and occupational entities, then the
7 public high school shall grant only limited access within the public high
8 school to military forces recruiters only to the extent to allow the military
9 forces recruiters to engage with students in grades ten through twelve (10-
10 12) in an in-person setting during normal school hours and at events that are
11 open to the public and outside of normal school hours.
12 (c) A military forces recruiter shall be permitted to engage with all
13 students in a public high school regardless of academic standing, class
14 enrollment, career aspirations, or participation in extracurricular
15 activities.
16 (d)(1) Each public high school shall provide an equal opportunity for
17 a military forces recruiter to present in person to students in grades ten
18 through twelve (10-12).
19 (2)(A) A military forces recruiter shall not be restricted by a
20 public school district to specific events, locations, or time periods unless
21 the restrictions to specific events, locations, or time periods apply to
22 prospective employers, institutions of higher education, career entities,
23 educational entities, and occupational entities.
24 (B) However, a restriction under subdivision (d)(2)(A) of
25 this section shall not prevent access of military forces recruiters to public
26 high schools as defined by this section.
27 (e)(1) A military forces recruiter shall be permitted to distribute
28 and collect information, administer surveys, and receive student contact
29 details in the same manner and under the same conditions as prospective
30 employers, institutions of higher education, career entities, educational
31 entities, and occupational entities.
32 (2) A public high school shall not impose additional privacy or
33 administrative barriers or parental consent requirements on a military forces
34 recruiter that are not imposed on prospective employers, institutions of
35 higher education, career entities, educational entities, and occupational
36 entities.
